<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos pajaroensis </i>is a long-lived, evergreen, sclerophyllous shrub that grows to 3 m tall. Leaves are ovate-triangular and green or slightly glaucous in color. Their shape is auriculate, clasping at the base. Plants usually have persistent gray shreddy bark on lower and middle stems. Plants lack a lignotuber and are obligate-seeders, and seeds collect in a seed bank as stones (Munz 1968, Greenlee and Langenheim 1990). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>A. pajaroensis </i>occupy a small area associated with <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>woodlands east of Elkhorn Slough and south of the Pajaro River in coastal Monterey Co. Fog is frequent, and yearly temperatures fluctuate relatively little. Total extent of the alliance is < 500 ha. They have been found on slopes and depressions of weathered sandstone below ridgelines. Stands typically change abruptly to a mixture of low-growing <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>and <i>Arctostaphylos hookeri </i>on more xeric ridges, plateaus, and sandstone outcrops. Stands in the Prunedale hills were resampled after 25 years, during a period in which fire has been excluded for at least 70 years. The dominance and height of <i>A. pajaroensis </i>has increased and understory species diversity decreased, caused by <i>A. pajaroensis </i>accumulating litter and overtopping and shading out other species (Van Dyke et al. 2001). <br/>
<br/>
Stands dominated by <i>A. pajaroensis </i>support five rare plants, including two federally listed ones. <i>Arctostaphylos hookeri </i>ssp. <i>hookeri, A. pajaroensis, Chorizanthe pungens </i>var. <i>pungens, Ericameria fasciculata, </i>and <i>Piperia yadonii </i>are CNPS list 1B plants. <i>Ceanothus cuneatus </i>var. <i>rigidus </i>is a CNPS list 4 plant. <i>Chorizanthe pungens </i>var. <i>pungens </i>is federally listed as threatened, and <i>P. yadonii </i>is listed as endangered. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
