<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Arctostaphylos pajaroensis </i>requires fire to germinate from viable seed buried in the soil. Its refractory seeds respond to heat scarification, and seedling establishment is abundant. The species is adapted to high-intensity, long-interval fires. Shrubs gain dominance with time, and they create a closed shrub canopy of tall shrubs, where a seed bank of buried seeds can develop in the soil. Historic fire intervals for the Monterey Bay area are estimated to be 10 to 100 years in general (Greenlee and Langenheim 1990). However, these estimates are probably not accurate for this alliance, and little is known about its natural disturbance regime. Deviation from the natural fire regime may favor obligate-seeding species such as <i>A. pajaroensis </i>(Van Dyke et al. 2001). In the long absence of fire, the presence of <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>increases in the mesic maritime chaparral stands of <i>A. pajaroensis, </i>which can gradually transition from manzanita to oak stands (Davis 1972, Griffin 1978).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
